The best approach for file system statics is the **`System.IO.Abstractions`** NuGet package — it's battle-tested and already covers `File.*` and `Directory.*`.

### 1. Install the package

```bash
dotnet add package System.IO.Abstractions
```

### 2. Register in DI

```csharp
builder.Services.AddSingleton<IFileSystem, FileSystem>();
```

### 3. Inject `IFileSystem` into your classes

```csharp
public class ConfigLoader(IFileSystem fileSystem)
{
    public string Load(string path)
        => fileSystem.File.ReadAllText(path);

    public void Save(string path, string content)
        => fileSystem.File.WriteAllText(path, content);

    public bool DirectoryExists(string path)
        => fileSystem.Directory.Exists(path);
}
```

### 4. Test with `MockFileSystem`

```bash
dotnet add <YourTestProject> package System.IO.Abstractions.TestingHelpers
```

```csharp
var mockFs = new MockFileSystem(new Dictionary<string, MockFileData>
{
    { "/data/config.json", new MockFileData("{\"key\": \"value\"}") }
});

var loader = new ConfigLoader(mockFs);

Assert.Equal("{\"key\": \"value\"}", loader.Load("/data/config.json"));

loader.Save("/data/out.txt", "hello");
Assert.Equal("hello", mockFs.File.ReadAllText("/data/out.txt"));

Assert.True(loader.DirectoryExists("/data"));
Assert.False(loader.DirectoryExists("/missing"));
```

**Key points:**
- Only wrap what you actually call — `IFileSystem` already covers your three statics.
- Register as `AddSingleton` since `FileSystem` is stateless.
- Avoid writing a custom wrapper — `System.IO.Abstractions` handles edge cases you'd otherwise miss.

Once you've updated your classes to accept `IFileSystem`, you can use the **migrate-static-to-wrapper** approach to bulk-replace the remaining call sites across the project.
